[[File:Luluabourg Constitution, Republic of the Congo (Léopoldville), published in Moniteur Congolais.pdf|page=2|thumb|The Luluabourg Constitution, published in ''Moniteur Congolais'']]

The '''Luluabourg Constitution''' ({{lang-fr|Constitution de Luluabourg}}) was the second constitution of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]. Functional from 1 August 1964 until November 1965, it was meant to replace the provisional ''Loi Fundamental'' that had been enacted when independence was declared in 1960. Unlike its predecessor, the Luluabourg Constitution featured a strong [[Executive (government)|executive]] presidency and carefully delineated [[federalism]] between the central government and the provinces. It also formalized the adoption of the name "Democratic Republic of the Congo", succeeding the name "[[Republic of the Congo (Léopoldville)|Republic of the Congo]]".

== Background ==
As was agreed upon by the participants in the [[Belgo-Congolese Round Table Conference]] in 1960, a formal constitution was to be agreed upon by the Congolese within three to four years of independence.{{sfn|Mutamba Makombo|2017|p=}}

== Summary ==
The Luluabourg Constitution was mostly a compensation for what its authors perceived to be the shortfalls of the ''Loi Fundamental''. Its principal features were a centralized and strengthened executive and a punctilious separation of responsibilities between the central and provincial governments.{{sfn|Leibholz|1966|p=658}}

=== National flag and state name ===
The constitution formally changed the name of the country from "[[Republic of the Congo (Léopoldville)|Republic of the Congo]]" to "Democratic Republic of the Congo" and adopted a new national flag.{{sfn|Kisangani|2016|pp=239–240}}

=== Presidency ===
According to the constitution, the president "determines and directs the policy of the state" and "establishes the framework of government action, supervises its application, and informs Parliament of its development".{{sfn|Leibholz|1966|p=658}} 

The president was to be selected by an [[electoral college]] composed of members of Parliament, members from every provincial assembly, and several delegates from the capital with the number of them being determined by how much representation they would be accorded to in Parliament based on population. The capital delegates and parliamentary delegates would meet in the capital to cast their vote, while the provincial assembly electors would do the same from their respective provincial capitals. All presidential candidates had to be at least 40 years of age. The president was to be chosen by the candidate with a simple majority. If this was not achieved on the first two ballots, then the candidate with a plurality on the third would become president.{{sfn|Leibholz|1966|p=659}}

=== Premiership ===
The office of prime minister was retained, thought its functions and responsibilities were largely reduced. The prime minister and all other cabinet ministers were to be named and revoked either individually or collectively by the president.{{sfn|Leibholz|1966|p=658}}

=== Nationality ===
Article 6 restricted Congolese nationality solely to persons whose ancestors were a part of an ethnic group that had lived in the Congo before 18 October 1908. This rule could be circumvented if a person submitted a formal request to change their nationality within 12 months of the promulgation of the constitution.{{sfn|Kisangani|2016|p=467}}

== Effects and criticisms ==
The Luluabourg Constitution denied citizenship to most Rwandan immigrants in the Congo.{{sfn|Kisangani|2016|p=467}} [[Marcel Bisukiro]], a former government minister, criticised it as discriminatory.{{sfn|The International Journal of African Historical Studies|1997|p=523}}

