{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}} {{Use British English|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox UK legislation |short_title=The Road Safety Act 2006<ref>The citation of this Act by this [[short title]] is authorised by [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2006/49/section/63 section 63] of this Act.</ref> |parliament=Parliament of the United Kingdom |long_title=An Act to make provision about road traffic, registration plates, vehicle and driver information, hackney carriages and private hire vehicles, and trunk road picnic areas. |year=2006 |statute_book_chapter=2006 c 49 |introduced_by= |territorial_extent= |royal_assent=8 November 2006 |commencement= |repeal_date= |amendments= |related_legislation= |repealing_legislation= |status= |original_text=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2006/49/contents/enacted |legislation_history=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/pabills/200506/road_safety.htm |revised_text=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2006/49/contents |}}
'''The Road Safety Act 2006''' (c 49) is an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. The provisions contained in the Act are designed to improve road safety and help achieve casualty reduction targets. The Government’s strategy for improving road safety was set out in the framework paper "Tomorrow’s Roads – safer for everyone".<ref>[http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/roadsafety/strategytargetsperformance/tomorrowsroadssaferforeveryone Tomorrow’s Roads – safer for everyone]</ref> The aim is to improve road safety and achieve casualty reduction targets of 40% of those killed and seriously injured and 50% reduction for children by 2010.
The Act creates a new criminal offence of causing death by careless, or inconsiderate, driving. This offence was introduced because of public concern about deaths on the roads and the minimal sentence allowed under the law as it was before the introduction of the Act. A person can now be sentenced summarily to 12 months (in England and Wales) or 6 months or a fine both or on indictment to 5 years or a fine or both. The Act also increased the penalty for use of a hand-held mobile phone or similar device. Section 26 provides for an obligatory endorsement (with disqualification at the court's discretion) for the offence.
The provisions of the Act cover: *Drink driving *Speeding *New offences *Penalties and enforcement *Driver training *Driver fatigue *Driver and vehicle licensing *Motor insurance
==Section 61 - Commencement== The following orders have been made under this section: *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2007/237/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 1) Order 2007] (S.I. 2007/237 (C.11)) *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2007/2472/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 2) Order 2007] (S.I. 2007/2472 (C.91)) *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2008/1864/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 3) Order 2008] (S.I. 2008/1864 (C.79)) *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2008/1918/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 4) Order 2008] (S.I. 2008/1918 (C.86)) *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2008/3164/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 5) Order 2008] (S.I. 2008/3164 (C.140)) *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2011/19/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 6) Order 2011] (S.I. 2011/19 (C.1)) *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2011/1119/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 7) Order 2011] (S.I. 2011/1119 (C.45)) *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2007/466/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 1) (England and Wales) Order 2007] (S.I. 2007/466 (C.18)) *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2007/3492/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 2) (England and Wales) Order 2007] (S.I. 2007/3492 (C.149)) *[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2008/1862/contents/made The Road Safety Act 2006 (Commencement No. 3) (England and Wales) Order 2008] (S.I. 2008/1862 (C.78))
